<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-integration-techniques" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Integration Techniques</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Dave and his team are planning out the heist, and we have seen how kinematics plays a role in the initial scouting mission and the chase from the security guards.
      You have seen that integration must be used to find <m>v(t)</m> from <m>a(t)</m>, and to find <m>x(t)</m> from <m>v(t)</m>.
      We will dedicate this section to learning some techniques for solving these integrals.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-the-antiderivative">
    <title>The Antiderivative</title>

    <p>
      Up until now, we have used the fundamental theorem of calculus to find the displacement through the velocity function, writing it as
      <me>
        x(t_2) - x(t_1) = \int_{t_1}^{t_2} v(t') \dd{t'}
      </me>.
      Remember that this is interpreted as a sum of small displacements each of magnitude <m>v(t) \Delta t</m>.
      We take the limit as <m>\Delta t \to 0</m> to get the integral.
      <me>
        \sum_{n=0}^{N-1} v(t_n) \Delta t \xrightarrow{\Delta t \to 0} \int_{t_1}^{t_2} v(t') \dd{t'}
      </me>.
    </p>

    <p>
      If we want to write an expression for <m>x(t)</m> for any arbitrary time <m>t</m>, we put the time in the upper limit of the integral:
      <me>
        x(t) - x(t_0) = \int_{t_0}^{t} v(t') \dd{t'}
      </me>.
      Here, we leave the lower limit as <m>t_0</m> to indicate that we are measuring the displacement from some initial time <m>t_0</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      There is a related, although not identical, concept called the <term>antiderivative</term>.
      It is essentially a shorthand for writing the integral where we don't specify the bounds.
      The equation above, when written in terms of the antiderivative, looks like
      <me>
        x(t) + C = \int v(t) \dd{t}
      </me>.
      We replace the lower limit with an arbitrary constant <m>C</m> to indicate that we don't know the initial position, and we can only determine the position up to an additive constant.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is known as an antiderivative, because the derivative of <m>x(t) + C</m> gives back the original expression in the integral (known as the <term>integrand</term>).
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the antiderivative of <m>v(t) = 3t^2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The derivative of <m>t^3</m> is <m>3t^2</m>, so one antiderivative of <m>v(t)</m> is <m>t^3</m>.
          However, since we can add any constant to this expression and still have the same derivative, we have infinitely many antiderivatives, which can be expressed as <m>t^3 + C</m>, where <m>C</m> is an arbitrary constant.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      An antiderivative is also called an <term>indefinite integral</term>, whereas the integral with specified bounds is called a <term>definite integral</term>.
    </p>

    <p>
      If an integrand is easily recognized as the derivative of some function, then we can easily find the antiderivative.
    </p>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the following antiderivatives:
          <md>
            <mrow>f(t) \amp = \int 5t^4 \dd{t}</mrow>
            <mrow>g(t) \amp = \int \frac{1}{t} \dd{t}</mrow>
            <mrow>h(t) \amp = \int \cos(t) \dd{t}</mrow>
            <mrow>k(t) \amp = \int \cos(2t) \dd{t}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The first three are straightforward:
          <md>
            <mrow>\int 5t^4 \dd{t} \amp = t^5 + C</mrow>
            <mrow>\int \frac{1}{t} \dd{t} \amp = \ln|t| + C</mrow>
            <mrow>\int \cos(t) \dd{t} \amp = \sin(t) + C</mrow>
          </md>
          Notice the absolute value in the second one, which is necessary because the logarithm is only defined for positive arguments, but <m>t</m> could be negative.
          The last one is a little trickier, but if you recall that the derivative of <m>\sin(2t)</m> is <m>2\cos(2t)</m>, then you can see that
          <me>
            \int \cos(2t) \dd{t} = \frac{1}{2} \sin(2t) + C
          </me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-integration-by-substitution">
    <title>Integration by Substitution</title>

    <p>
      Remember the chain rule? We had to use it a lot when we were taking derivatives of vectors in polar coordinates.
      There is a reverse version of the chain rule that we can use to evaluate integrals, called <term>integration by substitution</term>.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the antiderivative
          <me>
            x(t) = \int 2t \sqrt{t^2 + 1} \dd{t}.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Notice that we have in the integrand a function of <m>t^2 + 1</m>, and we also have the derivative of that function, <m>2t</m>, in the integrand.
          This means that the original function may have been differentiated using the chain rule, and we can reverse that process to find the antiderivative.
        </p>

        <p>
          To do so, we make the substitution <m>u = t^2 + 1</m>.
          Then we have <m>\dv{u}{t} = 2t</m>, which we can rearrange to get <m>2t \dd{t} = \dd{u}</m>.
          Substituting these into the integral, we get
          <me>
            x(t) = \int \sqrt{u} \dd{u} = \frac{2}{3} u^{3/2} + C = \frac{2}{3} (t^2 + 1)^{3/2} + C.
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      In addition to substituting to reverse the chain rule, another common use of substitution is to make <m>t</m> a trigonometric function, which, through the use of trigonometric identities, can simplify the integrand.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the following antiderivatives
          <md>
            <mrow>f(t) \amp = \int \frac{1}{\sqrt{a^2 - t^2}} \dd{t}</mrow>
            <mrow>g(t) \amp = \int \frac{1}{a^2 - t^2} \dd{t}</mrow>
          </md>
          by making the substitutions
          <md>
            <mrow>t = a \sin(\theta)</mrow>
            <mrow>t = a \tan(\theta)</mrow>
          </md>
          respectively.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The first can be solved by making the substitution <m>t = a \sin(\theta)</m>.
          Then we have <m>\dd{t} = a \cos(\theta) \dd{\theta}</m>.
          Notice that the radical simplifies to
          <me>
            \sqrt{a^2 - t^2} = \sqrt{a^2 - a^2 \sin^2(\theta)} = \sqrt{a^2 \cos^2(\theta)} = a \cos(\theta).
          </me>
          Substituting these into the integral, we get
          <me>
            f(t) = \int \frac{1}{a \cos(\theta)} a \cos(\theta) \dd{\theta} = \int \dd{\theta} = \theta + C = \arcsin\qty(\frac{t}{a}) + C.
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Similarly, the second can be solved by making the substitution <m>t = a \tan(\theta)</m>.
          Then we have <m>\dd{t} = a \sec^2(\theta) \dd{\theta}</m>.
          Notice that the denominator simplifies to
          <me>
            a^2 - t^2 = a^2 - a^2 \tan^2(\theta) = a^2 \sec^2(\theta).
          </me>
          Substituting these into the integral, we get
          <me>
            g(t) = \int \frac{1}{a^2 \sec^2(\theta)} a \sec^2(\theta) \dd{\theta} = \int \frac{1}{a} \dd{\theta} = \frac{1}{a} \theta + C = \frac{1}{a} \arctan\qty(\frac{t}{a}) + C.
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
</section>
